<DOC><DOCNO> AP900101-0007 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-01-90 0031EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     01-01 0711</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,680</SECOND><HEAD>Chief Justice Says More Judges Needed To Fight Drug War</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. courts need more judges, particularly inborder regions burdened with a heavy load of drug cases, says ChiefJustice William H. Rehnquist.   ``From the federal law enforcement perspective, the war on drugswill fail if the judiciary is not given the judgeships necessary todo the job,'' the Supreme Court chief said Sunday in his annualyear-end report on the federal court system.   ``Some courts, especially in border states, are approaching theouter limits of caseload and fatigue from handling drug-relatedcases,'' he said, noting that one in four criminal cases handled bythe federal courts is drug-related.   Rehnquist urged Congress to ``take immediate action'' to createthe 59 additional trial judgeships and 16 more appellate judgeshipsrequested last October by the U.S. Judicial Conference, thepolicy-making arm of the federal court system. Rehnquist heads theconference.   To date, Congress has authorized 575 federal trial judgeshipsand 168 appellate judgeships. No new judgeship has been createdsince 1984.</TEXT><BYLINE>___</BYLINE><HEAD>Three Jazz Greats Honored By National Endowment</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Boston music educator, a New York pianistand a Los Angeles trumpeteer received $20,000 fellowships from theNational Endowment for the Arts that also place them in the ``JazzHall of Fame.''   George Russell, Cecil Taylor and Gerald Wilson were awarded thejazz master fellowships Sunday for ``exceptional artistic merit inthe field of jazz.'' The trio joins 25 other jazz luminaries,including Dizzie Gillespie, Count Basie and Ella Fitzgerald, whohave been selected by the independent federal agency since theawards began in 1982.   Russell, 66, of Boston, is a composer, arranger, jazz theorist,drummer, pianist and band leader who has been on the faculty of theNew England Conservatory since 1969 and is leader of the LivingTime Orchestra.   Taylor, 60, of New York City, is a pianist and composer who wascited for his pioneering influences on modern jazz, including apiano playing style that features use of open palms, fists, elbowsand forearms.   Wilson, 71, of Los Angeles, is a Mississippi-born composer,arranger, band leader and trumpeter who once worked as a sidemanand arranger for Count Basie and Duke Ellington, and has ledseveral successful big bands of his own starting in the 1940s.</TEXT><BYLINE>___</BYLINE><HEAD>Panama's New Ambassador Appeals for Help</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Panama's newly appointed ambassador isappealing for contributions to a new non-profit corporation formedto help thousands of people left homeless or wounded by the U.Sinvasion of his country.   ``Urgent humanitarian needs are still unmet and all help isneeded. We appreciate all offers of assistance from our Americanfriends,''Carlos F. Rodriguez said Sunday in a statement announcingthe establishment of AID To Panama.   Dr. Jose Trinidad Castillero, Panama's minister of health, hasissued an urgent appeal for intravenous solutions, antibiotics,insulin, and anaesthetics. The shortage of blood is so severe, thatdoctors at Santo Tomas Hospital donated their own blood, Rodriguezsaid.   Checks and other contributions should be made to ``AID ToPanama'' and sent to either:   Catholic Relief Services, 209 W. Fayette Street, Baltimore,21202; or, ``AID To Panama'' Sun Bank (Acct. No. 01-890-0114-0297),777 Brickell Ave., Miami, Fla. 33131.</TEXT><BYLINE>___</BYLINE><HEAD>1989 Police Death Toll Drops</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The death toll among police officers killed inthe line of duty fell to 97 in 1989, down from 167 in 1988, saysthe National Association of Chiefs of Police.   Fifty officers died of gunshot wounds, 32 in traffic accidents,eight in plane crashes and seven others in stabbings, fights orother incidents on duty, the group said Sunday.   ``Increased use of bullet resistant jackets and the upgradedtraining in law enforcement agencies, we believe, has played a rolein reversing a trend that we thought would never end regarding thedeaths of law enforcement officers,'' David Waud, the association'schief of staff services, said in a statement.   The average age of officers killed was 27 in 1989. The mostdangerous day, on average, was Thursday and the most dangeroushours, between 10 p.m. and 2 a.m.   Texas led the count with 11 officers killed, followed by NewYork and Florida, each with eight, and Mississippi and California,each with seven.</TEXT></DOC>